{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17586963","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17586963"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T08:41:25+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T08:41:25+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15115"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15115","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15115"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.19,0,0.57,0.1,0.14]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7803"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"64575"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7803","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7803"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15115"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"50009"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"461"},{"type":"tags","id":"1094"},{"type":"tags","id":"4928"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"8127"},{"type":"tags","id":"8134"},{"type":"tags","id":"9598"},{"type":"tags","id":"10000"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"19028"},{"type":"contributions","id":"19033"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21285"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"64575","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/64575"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA patient presents with difficulty swallowing solid foods but has no problems swallowing liquids.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely underlying mechanism?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Disordered oesophageal peristalsis","Lower oesophageal sphincter spasm","Mechanical narrowing of the oesophagus","Oesophageal muscle weakness","Upper oesophageal sphincter dysfunction"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EWhen dysphagia affects solids but not liquids, this typically indicates a \u003Cstrong\u003Emechanical narrowing of the oesophagus\u003C/strong\u003E. This pattern occurs because liquids can still pass through a narrowed lumen while solids get stuck. Common causes include oesophageal strictures, rings, webs, or malignancy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDisordered oesophageal peristalsis\u003C/strong\u003E, \u003Cstrong\u003Elower oesophageal sphincter spasm\u003C/strong\u003E, \u003Cstrong\u003Eupper oesophageal sphincter dysfunction\u003C/strong\u003E, and \u003Cstrong\u003Eoesophageal muscle weakness\u003C/strong\u003E are all motility disorders that typically affect both solids and liquids from the onset of symptoms. This is because these conditions impact the fundamental mechanism of swallowing rather than creating a physical obstruction.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EProgressive dysphagia that starts with solids and later affects liquids is particularly concerning for oesophageal cancer, as the tumour gradually narrows the oesophageal lumen.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Dysphagia for solids but not liquids typically indicates a mechanical obstruction","Progressive dysphagia starting with solids then affecting liquids is characteristic of oesophageal cancer","Motility disorders typically affect both solids and liquids from onset"],"references":["Panebianco M, Marchese-Ragona R, Masiero S, Restivo DA. Dysphagia in neurological diseases: a literature review. Neurol Sci. 2020 Nov;41(11):3067-3073. doi: 10.1007/s10072-020-04495-2. Epub 2020 Jun 7. PMID: 32506360; PMCID: PMC7567719.","Wilkinson JM, Codipilly DC, Wilfahrt RP. Dysphagia: Evaluation an